#include <iostream>

// Function to find the nth Fibonacci number using recursion
int fib(int n) {
    if (n <= 0) {
        std::cerr << "Input should be a positive integer." << std::endl;
        exit(1);
    }
    else if (n == 1) {
        return 0;
    }
    else if (n == 2) {
        return 1;
    }
    else {
        return fib(n - 1) + fib(n - 2);
    }
}

int main() {
    int n;
    std::cout << "Enter a positive integer value of n: ";
    std::cin >> n;

    if (n < 0) {
        std::cerr << "Input should be a positive integer." << std::endl;
        exit(1);
    }

    int result = fib(n);
    std::cout << "The nth Fibonacci number is: " << result << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

## Explanation

This program will find the nth Fibonacci number by recursively summing the two preceding numbers. The `fib` function takes an integer `n` as input and returns the nth Fibonacci number.

The base cases for recursion are when `n` is 1 or 2, in which case the function returns 0 and 1, respectively. For `n` greater than 2, the function calls itself with the arguments `n - 1` and `n - 2`, then sums the results to obtain the nth Fibonacci number.

In the `main` function, the program prompts the user to enter a positive integer value of `n`, checks if the input is a positive integer, and then calls the `fib` function to find the nth Fibonacci number. The result is then displayed on the screen.

## Example Use Cases

*   Enter a positive integer value of `n`, and the program will display the corresponding nth Fibonacci number.

## Time Complexity

The time complexity of this recursive implementation is exponential, with a time complexity of O(2^n), due to the repeated calculations involved in the recursive calls.

## Space Complexity

The space complexity of this recursive implementation is also exponential, with a space complexity of O(n), due to the recursive call stack.

## Advice

For larger values of `n`, it is recommended to use an iterative implementation or memoization to improve performance, as the recursive implementation can be inefficient and may cause a stack overflow error.


